  "prompt": "When people say \"Maths\" instead of \"Math\" are they indicating plurality in some way?",
  "response": "No, when people say \"Maths\" instead of \"Math,\" they are not indicating plurality. It's simply a difference in regional English dialect.\n\n*   **\"Math\"** is the common abbreviation for mathematics in **American English**.\n*   **\"Maths\"** is the common abbreviation in **British English, Australian English, and other Commonwealth countries.**\n\nThe \"s\" on \"maths\" is a reflection of the full word \"mathematics,\" which is plural in form, even though it refers to a single field of study.\n\nSo, the choice between \"math\" and \"maths\" doesn't have to do with whether you're talking about one mathematical concept or many. It's just a matter of which dialect of English you're using.",
